# Subagent and skill routing

Use specialized helpers when scope or risk justifies it.

## 1) Subagent triggers

- **Broad exploration:** `explore` for architecture discovery or ownership mapping.
- **Planning:** apply the **`plan-major-change`** skill before large or ambiguous work; use **`technical-planning`** (or your tech-lead equivalent) to pressure-test high-risk plans.
- **Validation:** `test-runner` after behavior-changing edits; `verifier` before handoff on non-trivial work.
- **Docs:** `architecture-and-docs` when contracts or player-visible behavior changes.
- **Renames / terminology:** `migration-and-terminology` for field, type, API, or glossary cleanup.

Use additional domain agents from `.cursor/agents/` when they match the task (gameplay, audio, UI, etc.).

## 2) Skills

Before large procedural tasks, check `.cursor/skills/` for a matching workflow (brainstorm, sprint-plan, code-review, etc.).

For **Cursor governance** authoring, use user skills such as **`create-rule`** / **`create-skill`** when available.

## 3) Parallelization

- Launch independent investigations in parallel when safe.
- Do not delegate single-file needle queries to subagents.

## 4) Background execution

- Prefer background for long test passes, broad verification, or wide doc audits when the UI allows it.
- Poll background jobs before claiming completion.

## 5) Studio-style agents (optional)

When work matches a department role in `.cursor/docs/studio/agent-coordination-map.md`, pull in those agents for reviews or handoffs.

**Typical engineering routing:** gameplay / systems design → `gameplay-programmer` / `systems-designer`; rendering → **`rendering-specialist`**; web workers / WASM (if used) → `web-platform-specialist`; tools and editor pipelines → `tools-programmer` / `editor-tools-specialist` as appropriate.

## 6) Done criteria

The execution note should reflect which helper path was used when a trigger matched; otherwise proceed directly.
